  "market_context": "CL hourly chart shows price has swept a prior swing high near 68.86 and closed back inside the previous candle's range, presenting what initially appears to be a bearish reversal candle with a wick to be respected for a short-side continuation lower.",
  "key_observation": "On the 5-minute time frame, price opens, dips slightly, then immediately closes back over the 0.5 level of the hourly wick, disrespecting the wick. This invalidates the bearish reversal expectation and signals price is more likely to reach back up for the previous high.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the CL 1H chart, identify that price has taken out the prior swing high near 68.86 and closed back inside the range, forming a potential bearish reversal wick.",
    "Step 2: Establish the criterion: for the bearish scenario to hold, price on the 5-minute must form a high while respecting the 0.5 (mean threshold) of the hourly wick before expanding lower.",
    "Step 3: Drop down to the 5-minute time frame and watch the open — price opens, dips slightly lower (taking the previous 5M candle low), then closes back over the 50% level of the hourly wick.",
    "Step 4: Conclude that since the wick was disrespected (closed over the 0.5 level), it is now more likely that price reaches back up to take out the previous high rather than expanding lower.",
    "Step 5: Let the scenario play out and observe the expansion higher confirming the wick disrespect, with the previous high being taken out."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price disrespected the hourly wick on the 5-minute, expanded higher, and took out the previous high — the bearish reversal failed (no short trade taken; example demonstrates wick disrespect signal).",
  "lessons": "When a higher time frame wick is supposed to act as a reversal point, drop down to the lower time frame and observe whether the 0.5 level of that wick is respected. If price closes back over 50% of the wick early on, the reversal is invalidated and price is more likely to expand back toward the swept high/low.",
